
AI-Powered Chatbot Backend

This project is a production-ready backend service for an AI-powered chatbot system built using Django and Django REST Framework. The goal of this project is to design a scalable and cleanly structured backend that can manage authenticated users, maintain conversation sessions, and integrate with an AI model for automated responses.

Overview

This backend system supports authenticated users through JWT authentication. Each user can create multiple chat sessions, and each session maintains a full conversation history. The system integrates with an LLM (Large Language Model) to generate AI responses. If the AI service fails or times out, the system gracefully returns a fallback response instead of crashing.

The application is designed to work with SQLite during local development and PostgreSQL in production. The database configuration is controlled using environment variables.

Architecture

The system follows a layered architecture to maintain clean separation of concerns.

The API layer (Views) handles incoming HTTP requests and returns responses.
The validation layer (Serializers) validates input data and structures responses.
The data layer (Models) defines the database schema and relationships.
The service layer handles AI integration and business logic.

The request flow works as follows:

A user authenticates using JWT.
The user creates a chat session.
The user sends a message.
The message is stored in the database.
The system builds a prompt using session history.
The AI model generates a response.
The response is stored and returned to the user.

Database Design

The database uses a relational structure managed by Django ORM.

Each User can have multiple ChatSessions.
Each ChatSession can have multiple Messages.
Each Message stores a role (user or assistant) and the message content.

This design ensures support for multiple users, multiple sessions per user, and persistent chat history.

Authentication

Authentication is implemented using JWT (JSON Web Tokens) via djangorestframework-simplejwt.

The system provides access and refresh tokens.
Protected endpoints require the Authorization header with the format:
Bearer <access_token>

AI Integration

AI integration is handled in a separate service layer.
The system builds prompts using the entire session history to maintain context.
If the AI service fails, a fallback message is returned.
This ensures reliability and graceful error handling.

API Endpoints

Authentication endpoints:
POST /api/token/
POST /api/token/refresh/

Chat endpoints:
POST /api/chat/sessions/
GET /api/chat/sessions/{session_id}/
POST /api/chat/sessions/{session_id}/message/

API Documentation

Swagger documentation is available at:
/swagger/

Environment Configuration

The system uses environment variables for configuration.

Required variables include:
SECRET_KEY
DEBUG
USE_SQLITE
DATABASE_URL (for production)
OPENAI_API_KEY

Local Setup Instructions

Clone the repository and navigate to the project directory.

Create a virtual environment and activate it.

Install dependencies using pip install -r requirements.txt.

Create a .env file and add:

SECRET_KEY=your-secret
DEBUG=True
USE_SQLITE=True

Run database migrations using python manage.py migrate.

Create a superuser using python manage.py createsuperuser.

Start the server using python manage.py runserver.

Swagger can be accessed at [http://127.0.0.1:8000/swagger/](http://127.0.0.1:8000/swagger/)

Deployment

The project is configured for deployment on Railway.
It supports PostgreSQL in production using DATABASE_URL.
Gunicorn is used as the production WSGI server.
The database engine automatically switches based on environment variables.

Scalability Considerations

The system uses stateless JWT authentication, allowing horizontal scaling.
Database indexing is applied on session and timestamp fields for performance.
Rate limiting is enabled to prevent abuse.
AI logic is abstracted into a service layer for future extensibility.
Environment-based configuration makes the system deployment-ready.

Assumptions

Only one LLM provider is used.
No frontend is included as this is an API-only backend.
Basic rate limiting is sufficient for MVP usage.

